# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: web-midi
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:web-midi/api-midiaccess] This feature is not Baseline because it does not work in some of the most widely-used browsers.
[src:web-midi/api-midiaccess] The **`MIDIAccess`** interface of the Web MIDI API provides methods for listing MIDI input and output devices, and obtaining access to those devices.
[src:web-midi/api-midiaccess] Returns an instance of `MIDIInputMap` which provides access to any available MIDI input ports.
[src:web-midi/api-midiaccess] Returns an instance of `MIDIOutputMap` which provides access to any available MIDI output ports.
[src:web-midi/api-midiaccess] A boolean attribute indicating whether system exclusive support is enabled on the current MIDIAccess instance.
[src:web-midi/api-midiaccess] Called whenever a new MIDI port is added or an existing port changes state.
[src:web-midi/api-midiaccess] The `Navigator.requestMIDIAccess()` method returns a promise that resolves with a `MIDIAccess` object.
[src:web-midi/api-midiaccess] Information about the input and output ports is returned.
[src:web-midi/api-midiaccess] When a port changes state, information about that port is printed to the console.
[src:web-midi/api-midiinput] The **`MIDIInput`** interface of the Web MIDI API receives messages from a MIDI input port.
[src:web-midi/api-midiinput] Fired when the current port receives a MIDI message.
[src:web-midi/api-midiinput] In the following example the name of each `MIDIInput` is printed to the console.
[src:web-midi/api-midiinput] Then, `midimessage` events are listened for on all input ports.
[src:web-midi/api-midiinput] When a message is received the `MIDIMessageEvent.data` property is printed to the console.
[src:web-midi/api-midioutput] The **`MIDIOutput`** interface of the Web MIDI API provides methods to add messages to the queue of an output device, and to clear the queue of messages.
[src:web-midi/api-midioutput] Queues a message to be sent to the MIDI port.
[src:web-midi/api-midioutput] Clears any pending send data from the queue.
[src:web-midi/api-midioutput] The following example sends a middle C immediately on MIDI channel 1.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] MIDI also defines a file format that stores and exchanges the data.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] Advantages of MIDI include small file size, ease of modification and manipulation and a wide choice of electronic instruments and synthesizer or digitally sampled sounds.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] Before the development of MIDI, electronic musical instruments from different manufacturers had limited facilities to communicate with each other, principally using CV/gate connections.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] With MIDI, any MIDI-compatible keyboard (or other controller device) can be connected to any other MIDI-compatible sequencer, sound module, drum machine, synthesizer, or computer, even if they are made by different manufacturers.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] MIDI technology was standardized in 1983 by a panel of music industry representatives and is maintained by the MIDI Manufacturers Association (MMA).
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] All official MIDI standards are jointly developed and published by the MMA in Los Angeles and the MIDI Committee of the Association of Musical Electronics Industry (AMEI) in Tokyo.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] In 2016, the MMA established The MIDI Association (TMA) to support a global community of people who work, play, or create with MIDI.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] In the early 1980s, there was no standardized means of synchronizing electronic musical instruments manufactured by different companies.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] Manufacturers had their own proprietary standards to synchronize instruments, such as CV/gate, DIN sync and Digital Control Bus (DCB).
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] Ikutaro Kakehashi, the president of Roland, felt the lack of standardization was limiting the growth of the electronic music industry.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] In June 1981, he proposed developing a standard to the Oberheim Electronics founder Tom Oberheim, who had developed his own proprietary interface, the Oberheim Parallel Bus.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] Kakehashi felt that Oberheim's system was too cumbersome, and spoke to Dave Smith, the president of Sequential Circuits, about creating a simpler, cheaper alternative.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] While Smith discussed the concept with American companies, Kakehashi discussed it with Japanese companies Yamaha, Korg and Kawai.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] Representatives from all companies met to discuss the idea in October.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] Initially, only Sequential Circuits and the Japanese companies were interested.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] Using Roland's DCB as a basis, Smith and Sequential Circuits engineer Chet Wood devised a universal interface to allow communication between equipment from different manufacturers.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] Smith and Wood proposed this standard in a paper, *Universal Synthesizer Interface,* at the Audio Engineering Society show in October 1981.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] The standard was discussed and modified by representatives of Roland, Yamaha, Korg, Kawai, and Sequential Circuits.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] Kakehashi favored the name Universal Musical Interface (UMI), pronounced *you-me*, but Smith felt this was "a little corny".
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] However, he liked the use of *instrument* instead of *synthesizer*, and proposed *Musical Instrument Digital Interface* (MIDI).
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] Robert Moog, the president of Moog Music, announced MIDI in the October 1982 issue of *Keyboard*.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] At the 1983 Winter NAMM Show, Smith demonstrated a MIDI connection between Prophet 600 and Roland JP-6 synthesizers.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] The MIDI specification was published in August 1983.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] The MIDI standard was unveiled by Kakehashi and Smith, who received Technical Grammy Awards in 2013 for their work.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] In 1983, the first instruments were released with MIDI, the Roland Jupiter-6 and the Prophet 600.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] In 1983, the first MIDI drum machine, the Roland TR-909, and the first MIDI sequencer, the Roland MSQ-700, were released.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] The MIDI Manufacturers Association (MMA) was formed following a meeting of "all interested companies" at the 1984 Summer NAMM Show in Chicago.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] The MIDI 1.0 Detailed Specification was published at the MMA's second meeting at the 1985 Summer NAMM Show.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] The standard continued to evolve, adding standardized song files in 1991 (General MIDI) and adapted to new connection standards such as USB and FireWire.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] In 2016, the MIDI Association was formed to continue overseeing the standard.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] In 2017, an abridged version of MIDI 1.0 was published as an international standard IEC 63035.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] An initiative to create a 2.0 standard was announced in January 2019.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] The MIDI 2.0 standard was introduced at the 2020 Winter NAMM Show.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] The BBC cited MIDI as an early example of open-source technology.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] Smith believed MIDI could only succeed if every manufacturer adopted it, and so "we had to give it away".
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] MIDI's appeal was originally limited to professional musicians and record producers who wanted to use electronic instruments in the production of popular music.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] The standard allowed different instruments to communicate with each other and with computers, and this spurred a rapid expansion of the sales and production of electronic instruments and music software.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] This interoperability let one device control another, which reduced the hardware musicians needed.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] MIDI's introduction coincided with the dawn of the personal computer era and the introduction of samplers and digital synthesizers.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] The creative possibilities brought about by MIDI technology are credited for helping revive the music industry in the 1980s.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] MIDI introduced capabilities that transformed the way many musicians work.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] MIDI sequencing makes it possible for a user with no notation skills to build complex arrangements.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] A musical act with as few as one or two members, each operating multiple MIDI-enabled devices, can deliver a performance similar to that of a larger group of musicians.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] The expense of hiring outside musicians for a project can be reduced or eliminated, and complex productions can be realized on a system as small as a synthesizer with integrated keyboard and sequencer.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] MIDI also helped establish home recording.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] By performing preproduction in a home environment, an artist can reduce recording costs by arriving at a recording studio with a partially completed song.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] In 2022, the *Guardian* wrote that MIDI remained as important to music as USB was to computing, and represented "a crucial value system of cooperation and mutual benefit, one all but thrown out by today's major tech companies in favour of captive markets".
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] In 2005, Smith's MIDI Specification was inducted into the TECnology Hall of Fame, an honor given to "products and innovations that have had an enduring impact on the development of audio technology." As of 2022, Smith's original MIDI design is still in use.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] MIDI was invented so that electronic or digital musical instruments could communicate with each other and so that one instrument can control another.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] For example, a MIDI-compatible sequencer can trigger beats produced by a drum sound module.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] Analog synthesizers that have no digital component and were built prior to MIDI's development can be retrofitted with kits that convert MIDI messages into analog control voltages.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] When a note is played on a MIDI instrument, it generates a digital MIDI message that can be used to trigger a note on another instrument.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] The capability for remote control means smaller sound modules can replace full-sized instruments, and musicians can combine instruments for a fuller sound or to combine instrument sounds, such as acoustic piano and strings.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] MIDI also provides remote control over instrument parameters like volume, effects, etc.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] Synthesizers and samplers contain various tools for shaping an electronic or digital sound.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] Filters adjust timbre, and envelopes automate the way a sound evolves over time after a note is triggered.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] The frequency of a filter and the envelope attack (the time it takes for a sound to reach its maximum level), are examples of synthesizer parameters, and can be controlled remotely through MIDI.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] Effects devices have different parameters, such as delay feedback or reverb time.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] When a MIDI continuous controller number (CCN) is assigned to one of these parameters, the device responds to any messages it receives that are identified by that number.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] Controls such as knobs, switches, and pedals can be used to send these messages.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] A set of adjusted parameters can be saved to a device's internal memory as a *patch*, and these patches can be remotely selected by MIDI program changes.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] MIDI events can be sequenced with computer software, or in specialized hardware music workstations.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] Many digital audio workstations (DAWs) are specifically designed to work with MIDI as an integral component.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] MIDI piano rolls have been developed in many DAWs so that the recorded MIDI messages can be easily modified.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] These tools allow composers to audition and edit their work much more quickly and efficiently than did older solutions, such as multitrack recording.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] Compositions can be programmed for MIDI that are impossible for human performers to play.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] Because a MIDI performance is a sequence of commands that create sound, MIDI recordings can be manipulated in ways that audio recordings cannot.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] It is possible to change the key, instrumentation or tempo of a MIDI arrangement, and to reorder its individual sections, or even edit individual notes.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] The ability to compose ideas and quickly hear them played back enables composers to experiment.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] Algorithmic composition programs provide computer-generated performances that can be used as song ideas or accompaniment.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] Some composers may take advantage of the standard, portable set of commands and parameters in MIDI 1.0 and General MIDI (GM) to share musical data files among various electronic instruments.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] The data composed via the sequenced MIDI recordings can be saved as a *standard MIDI file* (SMF), digitally distributed, and reproduced by any computer or electronic instrument that also adheres to the same MIDI, GM, and SMF standards.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] MIDI data files are much smaller than corresponding recorded audio files.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] The personal computer market stabilized at the same time that MIDI appeared, and computers became a viable option for music production.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] In 1983 computers started to play a role in mainstream music production.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] In the years immediately after the 1983 ratification of the MIDI specification, MIDI features were adapted to several early computer platforms.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] The Yamaha CX5M introduced MIDI support and sequencing in an MSX system in 1984.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] The spread of MIDI on home computers was largely facilitated by Roland Corporation's MPU-401, released in 1984, as the first MIDI-equipped sound card, capable of MIDI sound processing and sequencing.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] After Roland sold MPU sound chips to other sound card manufacturers, it established a universal standard MIDI-to-PC interface.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] The widespread adoption of MIDI led to computer-based MIDI software being developed.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] Soon after, a number of platforms began supporting MIDI, including the Apple II, Macintosh, Commodore 64, Amiga, Acorn Archimedes, and IBM PC compatibles.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] The 1985 Atari ST shipped with MIDI ports as part of the base system.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] In 2015, Retro Innovations released the first MIDI interface for a VIC-20, making the computer's four voices available to electronic musicians and retro-computing enthusiasts for the first time.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] Retro Innovations also makes a MIDI interface cartridge for Tandy Color Computer and Dragon computers.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] Chiptune musicians also use retro gaming consoles to compose, produce and perform music using MIDI interfaces.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] Custom interfaces are available for the Family Computer/Nintendo Entertainment System, Game Boy, Game Boy Advance and Sega Mega Drive/Sega Genesis.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] Rather, it is a set of instructions – for example, for pitch or tempo – and can use a thousand times less disk space than the equivalent recorded audio.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] Due to their tiny filesize, fan-made MIDI arrangements became an attractive way to share music online, before the advent of broadband internet access and multi-gigabyte hard drives.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] The major drawback to this is the wide variation in quality of users' audio cards, and in the actual audio contained as samples or synthesized sound in the card that the MIDI data only refers to symbolically.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] Even a sound card that contains high-quality sampled sounds can have inconsistent quality from one sampled instrument to another.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] Early budget-priced cards, such as the AdLib and the Sound Blaster and its compatibles, used a stripped-down version of Yamaha's frequency modulation synthesis (FM synthesis) technology played back through low-quality digital-to-analog converters.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] The low-fidelity reproduction of these ubiquitous cards was often assumed to somehow be a property of MIDI itself.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] This created a perception of MIDI as low-quality audio, while in reality MIDI itself contains no sound, and the quality of its playback depends entirely on the quality of the sound-producing device.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] The **Standard MIDI File** (**SMF**) is a file format that provides a standardized way to save, transport, and open music sequences in other systems.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] The standard was developed and is maintained by the MMA, and usually uses a `.mid` extension.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] The compact size of these files led to their widespread use in computers, mobile phone ringtones, webpage authoring and musical greeting cards.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] These files are intended for universal use and include such information as note values, timing and track names.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] Lyrics may be included as metadata, and can be displayed by karaoke machines.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] SMFs are created as an export format of software sequencers or hardware workstations.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] They organize MIDI messages into one or more parallel tracks and time-stamp the events so that they can be played back in sequence.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] A header contains the arrangement's track count, tempo and indicates which of three SMF formats the file uses.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] A type 0 file contains the entire performance, merged onto a single track, while type 1 files may contain any number of tracks that are performed synchronously.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] Type 2 files are rarely used and store multiple arrangements, with each arrangement having its own track to be played in sequence.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] Microsoft Windows bundles SMFs together with Downloadable Sounds (DLS) in a Resource Interchange File Format (RIFF) wrapper, as **RMID files** with a `.rmi` extension.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] RIFF-RMID has been deprecated in favor of **Extensible Music Files** (XMF).
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] The main advantage of the personal computer in a MIDI system is that it can serve a number of different purposes, depending on the software that is loaded.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] Multitasking allows simultaneous operation of programs that may be able to share data with each other.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] Sequencing software can be used to manipulate recorded MIDI data with standard computer editing features such as cut, copy and paste and drag and drop.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] Keyboard shortcuts can be used to streamline workflow, and, in some systems, editing functions may be invoked by MIDI events.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] The sequencer can set each channel to play a different sound and gives a graphical overview of the arrangement.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] A variety of editing tools are made available, including a notation display or scorewriter that can be used to create printed parts for musicians.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] Tools such as looping, quantization, randomization, and transposition simplify the arranging process.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] Beat creation is simplified, and groove templates can be used to duplicate another track's rhythmic feel.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] Realistic expression can be added through the manipulation of real-time controllers.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] Mixing can be performed, and MIDI can be synchronized with recorded audio and video tracks.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] Work can be saved, and transported between different computers or studios.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] Sequencers may take alternate forms, such as drum pattern editors that users can use to create beats by clicking on pattern grids, and loop sequencers such as ACID Pro, which combine MIDI with prerecorded audio loops whose tempos and keys are matched to each other.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] Cue-list sequencing is used to trigger dialogue, sound effect, and music cues in stage and broadcast production.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] With MIDI, notes played on a keyboard can automatically be transcribed to sheet music.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] Scorewriting software typically lacks advanced sequencing tools and is optimized for the creation of a neat, professional printout designed for live instrumentalists.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] These programs provide support for dynamics and expression markings, chord and lyric display, and complex score styles.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] Software is available that can print scores in braille.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] Notation programs include Finale, Encore, Sibelius, MuseScore and Dorico.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] SmartScore software can produce MIDI files from scanned sheet music.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] Users can program their equipment through the patch editor as a computer interface.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] These became essential with the appearance of complex synthesizers such as the Yamaha FS1R, which contained several thousand programmable parameters, but had an interface that consisted of fifteen tiny buttons, four knobs and a small LCD.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] Some editors are designed for a specific instrument or effects device, while other, *universal* editors support a variety of equipment, and ideally can control the parameters of every device in a setup through the use of System Exclusive messages.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] System Exclusive messages use the MIDI protocol to send information about the synthesizer's parameters.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] Patch librarians have the specialized function of organizing the sounds in a collection of equipment and exchanging entire banks of sounds between an instrument and a computer.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] In this way the device's limited patch storage is augmented by a computer's much greater disk capacity.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] Once transferred to the computer, custom patches can be shared with other owners of the same instrument.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] Universal editor/librarians that combine the two functions were once common, and included Opcode Systems' Galaxy, eMagic's SoundDiver, and MOTU's Unisyn.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] Although these older programs have been largely abandoned with the trend toward computer-based synthesis using virtual instruments, several editor/librarians remain available, including Coffeeshopped Patch Base, Sound Quest's Midi Quest, and several editors from Sound Tower.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] Native Instruments' Kore was an effort to bring the editor/librarian concept into the age of software instruments, but was abandoned in 2011.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] Programs that can dynamically generate accompaniment tracks are called *auto-accompaniment* programs.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] These create a full-band arrangement in a style that the user selects and sends the result to a MIDI sound-generating device for playback.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] The generated tracks can be used as educational or practice tools, as accompaniment for live performances, or as a songwriting aid.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] Computers can use software to generate sounds, which then pass through a digital-to-analog converter (DAC) to a power amplifier and loudspeaker system.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] The number of sounds that can be played simultaneously (the polyphony) is dependent on the power of the computer's CPU, as are the sample rate and bit depth of playback, which directly affect sound quality.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] Synthesizers implemented in software are subject to timing issues that are not necessarily present with hardware instruments, whose dedicated operating systems are not subject to interruption from background tasks as desktop operating systems are.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] These timing issues can cause synchronization problems, and clicks and pops when sample playback is interrupted.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] Software synthesizers also may exhibit additional latency in their sound generation.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] The roots of software synthesis go back as far as the 1950s, when Max Mathews of Bell Labs wrote the MUSIC-N programming language, which was capable of non-real-time sound generation.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] Reality, by Dave Smith's Seer Systems was an early synthesizer that ran directly on a host computer's CPU.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] Reality achieved a low latency through tight driver integration, and therefore could run only on Creative Labs soundcards.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] Syntauri Corporation's Alpha Syntauri was another early software-based synthesizer.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] It ran on the Apple IIe computer and used a combination of software and the computer's hardware to produce additive synthesis.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] Some systems use dedicated hardware to reduce the load on the host CPU, as with Symbolic Sound Corporation's Kyma System, and the Creamware/Sonic Core Pulsar/SCOPE systems, which power an entire recording studio's worth of instruments, effect units, and mixers.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] The ability to construct full MIDI arrangements entirely in computer software allows a composer to render a finalized result directly as an audio file.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] Until the mid-1990s, floppy disks were the primary distribution medium for IBM PC compatible games.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] The small size of MIDI files made them a viable means of providing soundtracks.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] Prior to Windows 95, games typically used either Ad Lib or Sound Blaster audio cards.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] These cards use FM synthesis, which generates sound through modulation of sine waves.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] John Chowning, the technique's pioneer, theorized that the technology would be capable of accurate recreation of any sound if enough sine waves were used, but most computer audio cards performed FM synthesis with only two sine waves.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] Combined with the cards' 8-bit audio, this resulted in a sound described as "artificial" and "primitive".
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] Wavetable daughterboards that were later available provided audio samples that could be used in place of the FM sound.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] These were expensive, but often used the sounds from respected MIDI instruments such as the E-mu Proteus.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] The computer industry moved in the mid-1990s toward wavetable-based soundcards with 16-bit playback but standardized on a 2 MB of wavetable storage, a space too small to fit good-quality samples of 128 General MIDI instruments plus drum kits.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] To make the most of the limited space, some manufacturers stored 12-bit samples and expanded those to 16 bits on playback.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] Despite its association with music devices, MIDI can control any electronic or digital device that can read and process a MIDI command.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] MIDI has been adopted as a control protocol in a number of non-musical applications.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] MIDI Show Control uses MIDI commands to direct stage lighting systems and to trigger cued events in theatrical productions.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] VJs and turntablists use it to cue clips, and to synchronize equipment, and recording systems use it for synchronization and automation.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] Wayne Lytle, the founder of Animusic, derived a system he dubbed MIDIMotion, which he used to produce the *Animusic* series of computer-animated music video albums.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] Animusic later designed its own animation software specifically for MIDIMotion called Animotion.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] Apple Motion allows for a similar control of animation parameters through MIDI.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] The 1987 first-person shooter game *MIDI Maze* and the 1990 Atari ST puzzle video game *Oxyd* use MIDI to network computers together.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] Per the original MIDI 1.0 standard, cables terminate in a 180° five-pin DIN connector (DIN 41524).
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] Typical applications use only three of the five conductors: a ground wire (pin 2), and a balanced pair of conductors (pins 4 and 5) that carry the MIDI signal as an electric current.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] This connector configuration can only carry messages in one direction, so a second cable is necessary for two-way communication.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] Some proprietary applications, such as phantom-powered footswitch controllers, use the spare pins for direct current (DC) power transmission.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] Opto-isolators keep MIDI devices electrically separated from their MIDI connections, which prevents ground loops and protects equipment from voltage spikes.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] There is no error detection capability in MIDI, so the maximum cable length is set at 15 meters (49 ft) to limit interference.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] To save space, some MIDI devices (smaller ones in particular) started using 3.5 mm TRS phone connectors (also known as audio minijack connectors).
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] This became widespread enough that the MIDI Manufacturers' Association standardized the wiring.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] The MIDI-over-minijack standards document also recommends the use of 2.5 mm connectors over 3.5 mm ones to avoid confusion with audio connectors.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] Most devices do not copy messages from their input to their output port.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] A third type of port, the *thru* port, emits a copy of everything received at the input port, to pass data forwarded to another instrument in a daisy-chain arrangement.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] Not all devices feature thru ports, and devices that lack the ability to generate MIDI data, such as effects units and sound modules, may not include out ports.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] Each device in a daisy chain adds delay to the system.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] This can be avoided by using a MIDI thru box, which contains several outputs that provide an exact copy of the box's input signal.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] A MIDI merger combines input from multiple devices into a single stream, so multiple controllers can connect to a single device.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] A MIDI switcher switches between multiple devices, and eliminates physical repatch cables.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] MIDI routers combine all these functions—with multiple inputs and outputs, able to rout any combination of input channels to any combination of outputs.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] Routing setups can be created using computer software, stored in memory, and selected by MIDI program change commands.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] This enables the devices to function as standalone MIDI routers in situations where no computer is present.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] MIDI data processors are used for utility tasks and special effects.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] These include MIDI filters, which remove unwanted MIDI data from the stream, and MIDI delays, effects that send a repeated copy of the input data at a set time.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] A computer MIDI interface's main function is to synchronize communications between the MIDI device and the computer.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] Some computer sound cards include a standard MIDI connector, whereas others connect by any of various means that include the D-subminiature DA-15 game port, USB, FireWire, Ethernet or a proprietary connection.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] The increasing use of USB connectors in the 2000s has led to the availability of MIDI-to-USB data interfaces that can transfer MIDI channels to USB-equipped computers.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] Some MIDI keyboard controllers are equipped with USB jacks, and can be connected directly to computers that run music software.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] MIDI's serial transmission leads to timing problems.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] A three-byte MIDI message requires nearly 1 millisecond for transmission.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] Because MIDI is serial, it can only send one event at a time.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] If an event is sent on two channels at once, the event on the second channel cannot transmit until the first one is finished, and so is delayed by 1 ms.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] If an event is sent on all channels at the same time, the last channel's transmission is delayed by as much as 16 ms.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] This contributed to the rise of MIDI interfaces with multiple in- and out-ports, because timing improves when events are spread between multiple ports as opposed to multiple channels on the same port.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] The term *MIDI slop* refers to audible timing errors that result when MIDI transmission is delayed.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] There are two types of MIDI controllers: performance controllers that generate notes and are used to perform music, and controllers that may not send notes, but transmit other types of real-time events.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] Many devices are a combination of the two types.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] Keyboards are by far the most common type of MIDI controller.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] MIDI was designed with keyboards in mind and any controller that is not a keyboard is considered an "alternative" controller.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] Nevertheless, some features of the keyboard playing for which MIDI was designed do not fully capture other instruments' capabilities; Jaron Lanier cites the standard as an example of technological "lock-in" that unexpectedly limited what was possible to express.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] Some of these shortcomings have been addressed in extensions to the protocol.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] Software synthesizers offer great power and versatility, but some players feel that division of attention between a MIDI keyboard and a computer keyboard and mouse robs some of the immediacy from the playing experience.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] Devices dedicated to real-time MIDI control provide an ergonomic benefit and can provide a greater sense of connection with the instrument than an interface that is accessed through a computer.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] Controllers may be general-purpose devices that are designed to work with a variety of equipment, or they may be designed to work with a specific piece of software.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] Examples of the latter include Akai's APC40 controller for Ableton Live, and Korg's MS-20ic controller, a reproduction of the control panel on their MS-20 analog synthesizer.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] The MS-20ic controller includes patch cables that can be used to control signal routing in their virtual reproduction of the MS-20 synthesizer and can also control third-party devices.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] A MIDI instrument contains ports to send and receive MIDI signals, a CPU to process those signals, an interface for user programming, audio circuitry to generate sound, and controllers.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] The operating system and factory sounds are often stored in a read-only memory (ROM) unit.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] A MIDI instrument can also be a stand-alone module (without a piano-style keyboard) consisting of a General MIDI soundboard (GM, GS and XG), onboard editing, including transposing, MIDI instrument selection and adjusting volume, pan, reverb levels and other MIDI controllers.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] Typically, the MIDI module includes a screen, so the user can view information for the currently selected function.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] Synthesizers may employ any of a variety of sound generation techniques.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] They may include an integrated keyboard or may exist as sound modules that generate sounds when triggered by an external controller, such as a MIDI keyboard.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] Sound modules are typically designed to mount in a 19-inch rack.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] Manufacturers commonly produce a synthesizer in both standalone and rack-mounted versions, and often offer the keyboard version in a variety of sizes.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] A sampler can record and digitize audio, store it in random-access memory (RAM), and play it back.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] With a sampler, users typically can edit a sample and save it to a hard disk, apply effects to it, and shape it with the same tools that subtractive synthesizers use.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] They also may be available in either keyboard or rack-mounted form.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] Instruments that generate sounds through sample playback, but have no recording capabilities, are known as "ROMplers".
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] Samplers did not become established as viable MIDI instruments as quickly as synthesizers did due to the expense of memory and processing power at the time.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] The first low-cost MIDI sampler was the Ensoniq Mirage, introduced in 1984.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] MIDI samplers are typically limited by displays that are too small to use to edit sampled waveforms, although some can be connected to a computer monitor.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] Drum machines typically are sample playback devices that specialize in drum and percussion sounds.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] They commonly contain a sequencer for creating drum patterns and arranging them into a song.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] There often are multiple audio outputs so that each sound or group of sounds can be routed to a separate output.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] The individual drum voices may be playable from another MIDI instrument or from a sequencer.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] Analog sequencers use CV/Gate signals to control pre-MIDI analog synthesizers.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] MIDI sequencers typically are operated by transport features modeled after those of tape decks.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] They are capable of recording MIDI performances and arranging them into individual tracks using a multitrack recording paradigm.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] Music workstations combine controller keyboards with an internal sound generator and a sequencer.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] These can be used to build complete arrangements and play them back using their own internal sounds and function as self-contained music production studios.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] They commonly include file storage and transfer capabilities.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] Some effects units can be remotely controlled via MIDI.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] For example, the Eventide H3000 Ultra-harmonizer allows such extensive MIDI control that it is playable as a synthesizer.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] The Drum Buddy, a pedal-format drum machine, has a MIDI connection so that it can have its tempo synchronized with a looper pedal or time-based effects such as delay.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] MIDI messages are made up of 8-bit bytes transmitted at 31,250 (±1%) baud using 8-N-1 asynchronous serial communication as described in the figure.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] The first bit of each byte identifies whether the byte is a *status* byte or a *data* byte, and is followed by seven bits of information.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] A MIDI link can carry sixteen independent channels, numbered 1–16.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] A device may listen to specific channels and ignore messages on other channels (*omni off* mode), or it can listen to all channels, effectively ignoring the channel address (*omni on*).
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] A device that is polyphonic can sound multiple notes simultaneously, until the device's polyphony limit is reached, or the notes reach the end of their decay envelope, or explicit *note-off* MIDI commands are received.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] A device that is monophonic instead terminates any previous note when new *note-on* commands arrive.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] A MIDI message is an instruction that controls some aspect of the receiving device.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] A MIDI message consists of a status byte, which indicates the type of the message, followed by up to two data bytes that contain the parameters.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] MIDI messages can be *channel messages* sent on only one of the 16 channels and monitored only by devices on that channel, or *system messages* that all devices receive.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] Each receiving device ignores data not relevant to its function.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] There are five types of message: Channel Voice, Channel Mode, System Common, System Real-Time, and System Exclusive.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] Channel Voice messages transmit real-time performance data over a single channel.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] MIDI notes are numbered from 0 to 127 assigned to C−1 to G9, with middle C4 at note number 60.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] This extends beyond the 88-note piano range from A0 to C8 and corresponds to a frequency range of 8.175799 to 12543.85 Hz.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] System Exclusive (**SysEx**) messages send information about a synthesizer's functions, rather than performance data such as note value and loudness.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] Because they can include functionality beyond what the MIDI standard provides, they are a major reason for the flexibility and longevity of the MIDI standard.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] Manufacturers use them to create proprietary messages that control their equipment more thoroughly than the limitations of standard MIDI messages.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] The MIDI Manufacturers Association issues a unique identification number to MIDI companies.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] These are included in SysEx messages, to ensure that only the specifically addressed device responds to the message, while all others know to ignore it.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] Many instruments also include a SysEx ID setting, so a controller can address two devices of the same model independently.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] Devices typically do not respond to every type of message defined by the MIDI specification.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] The MIDI implementation chart was standardized by the MMA as a way for users to see what specific capabilities an instrument has, and how it responds to messages.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] A populated MIDI implementation chart is usually published as part of the documentation for MIDI devices.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] "DIN / TRS" in this schematic indicates that either a DIN connector or a TRS phone connector may be used.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] To transmit a logic 0 and a start bit, the sender's UART produces a low voltage.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] This results in a nominal 5 milliamperes current flow sourced from the sender's high voltage supply, which travels rightwards along the red lines though the shielded twisted-pair cable and into the receiver's opto-isolator.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] The current exits the opto-isolator and returns back leftwards along the blue lines into the sender's UART, which sinks the current.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] Resistors R1 and R2 limit the current and are equal to provide a balanced impedance.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] This current turns on the opto-isolator's LED and phototransistor, so the receiver's UART can read the signal with the help of pull-up resistor R3 to the receiver's voltage supply.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] While the supplies in the original specification are 5 volts, the receiver and sender may use different voltage levels.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] To transmit a logic 1, a stop bit, and while idle, the sender's UART produces the same high voltage as its voltage supply provides, which results in no current flow.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] MIDI's flexibility and widespread adoption have led to many refinements of the standard, enabling its application to purposes beyond those originally intended.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] MIDI allows the selection of an instrument's sounds through program change messages, but there is no guarantee that any two instruments have the same sound at a given program location.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] Program #0 may be a piano on one instrument, or a flute on another.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] The General MIDI (GM) standard was established in 1991, and provides a standardized sound bank that allows a Standard MIDI File created on one device to sound similar when played back on another.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] GM specifies a bank of 128 sounds arranged into 16 families of eight related instruments, and assigns a specific program number to each instrument.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] Any given program change selects the same instrument sound on any GM-compatible instrument.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] Percussion instruments are placed on channel 10, and a specific MIDI note value is mapped to each percussion sound.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] The GM standard eliminates variation in note mapping.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] Some manufacturers had disagreed over what note number should represent middle C, but GM specifies that note number 69 plays A440, which in turn fixes middle C as note number 60.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] GM-compliant devices must offer 24-note polyphony.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] GM-compatible devices must respond to velocity, aftertouch, and pitch bend, set to specified default values at startup, and must support certain controller numbers such as for sustain pedal, and Registered Parameter Numbers (RPNs).
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] A simplified version of GM, called *GM Lite*, is used for devices with limited processing power.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] A general opinion quickly formed that the GM's 128-instrument sound set was not large enough.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] Roland's General Standard, or Roland GS, included additional sounds, drumkits and effects, provided a *bank select* command that could be used to access them, and used MIDI Non-Registered Parameter Numbers (NRPNs) to access its new features.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] Yamaha's Extended General MIDI, or Yamaha XG, followed in 1994.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] XG similarly offered extra sounds, drumkits and effects, but used standard controllers instead of NRPNs for editing, and increased polyphony to 32 voices.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] Both standards feature backward compatibility with the GM specification but are not compatible with each other.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] Neither standard has been adopted beyond its creator, but both are commonly supported by music software titles.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] Member companies of Japan's AMEI developed the General MIDI Level 2 specification in 1999.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] GM2 maintains backward compatibility with GM, but increases polyphony to 32 voices, standardizes several controller numbers such as for sostenuto and soft pedal (*una corda*), RPNs and Universal System Exclusive Messages, and incorporates the MIDI Tuning Standard.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] GM2 is the basis of the instrument selection mechanism in Scalable Polyphony MIDI (SP-MIDI), a MIDI variant for low-power devices that allows the device's polyphony to scale according to its processing power.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] Most MIDI synthesizers use equal temperament tuning.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] The MIDI tuning standard (MTS), ratified in 1992, allows alternate tunings.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] MTS allows microtunings that can be loaded from a bank of up to 128 patches, and allows real-time adjustment of note pitches.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] Manufacturers are not required to support the standard.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] Those who do are not required to implement all of its features.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] A sequencer can drive a MIDI system with its internal clock, but when a system contains multiple sequencers, they must synchronize to a common clock.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] MIDI timecode (MTC), developed by Digidesign, implements SysEx messages developed specifically for timing purposes, and can translate to and from the SMPTE timecode standard.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] MIDI interfaces such as Mark of the Unicorn's MIDI Timepiece can convert SMPTE code to MTC.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] While MIDI clock is based on tempo, timecode is based on frames and is independent of tempo.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] MTC, like SMPTE timecode, includes position information and can recover in the event of a dropout.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] MIDI Machine Control (MMC) consists of a set of SysEx commands that operate the transport controls of hardware recording devices.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] MMC lets a sequencer send *Start*, *Stop*, and *Record* commands to a connected tape deck or hard disk recording system, and to fast-forward or rewind the device to start playback at the same point as the sequencer.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] No synchronization data is involved, although the devices may synchronize through MTC.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] MIDI Show Control (MSC) is a set of SysEx commands for sequencing and remotely cueing show control devices such as lighting, music and sound playback, and motion control systems.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] Applications include stage productions, museum exhibits, recording studio control systems, and amusement park attractions.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] One solution to MIDI timing problems is to mark MIDI events with the times they are to be played, transmit them beforehand, and store them in a buffer in the receiving device.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] Sending data beforehand reduces the likelihood that a busy passage overwhelms the transmission link.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] Once stored in the receiver, the information is no longer subject to timing issues associated with MIDI or USB interfaces and can be played with a high degree of accuracy.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] MIDI timestamping only works when both hardware and software support it.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] MOTU's MTS, eMagic's AMT, and Steinberg's Midex 8 had implementations that were incompatible with each other, and required users to own software and hardware manufactured by the same company to work.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] Timestamping is built into FireWire MIDI interfaces, Mac OS X Core Audio, and Linux ALSA Sequencer.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] An unforeseen capability of SysEx messages was their use for transporting audio samples between instruments.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] This led to the development of the sample dump standard (SDS), which established a new SysEx format for sample transmission.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] SDS was later augmented with a pair of commands that allow the transmission of information about sample loop points, without requiring that the entire sample be transmitted.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] The Downloadable Sounds (DLS) specification, ratified in 1997, allows mobile devices and computer sound cards to expand their wave tables with downloadable sound sets.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] The DLS Level 2 specification followed in 2006, and defined a standardized synthesizer architecture.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] The Mobile DLS standard combines DLS banks with SP-MIDI as self-contained Mobile XMF files.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] MIDI Polyphonic Expression (MPE) is a method that lets musicians control pitch bend, and other expressive controls continuously for individual notes.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] MPE works by assigning each note to its own MIDI channel so that controller messages can be applied to each note individually.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] The specifications were released in November 2017 by AMEI and in January 2018 by the MMA.
[src:web-midi/midi-p01] Instruments like the Continuum Fingerboard, LinnStrument, ROLI Seaboard, Sensel Morph, and Eigenharp let users control pitch, timbre, and other nuances for individual notes within chords.
[src:web-midi/midi-p02] In addition to using a 31.25 kbit/s current-loop over a DIN connector, the same data can be transmitted over different hardware transports such as USB, FireWire, and Ethernet.
[src:web-midi/midi-p02] Members of the USB-IF in 1999 developed a standard for MIDI over USB, the "Universal Serial Bus Device Class Definition for MIDI Devices".
[src:web-midi/midi-p02] MIDI over USB has become increasingly common as other interfaces that had been used for MIDI connections (ISA card, game port, etc.) disappeared from personal computers.
[src:web-midi/midi-p02] Linux, Microsoft Windows, Macintosh OS X, and Apple iOS operating systems include standard class drivers to support devices that use the "Universal Serial Bus Device Class Definition for MIDI Devices".
[src:web-midi/midi-p02] Apple Computer developed the FireWire interface during the 1990s.
[src:web-midi/midi-p02] It began to appear on digital video (DV) cameras toward the end of the decade, and on G3 Macintosh models in 1999.
[src:web-midi/midi-p02] It was created for use with multimedia applications.
[src:web-midi/midi-p02] Unlike USB, FireWire uses intelligent controllers that can manage their own transmission without attention from the main CPU.
[src:web-midi/midi-p02] As with standard MIDI devices, FireWire devices can communicate with each other with no computer present.
[src:web-midi/midi-p02] The Octave-Plateau Voyetra-8 synthesizer was an early MIDI implementation using XLR3 connectors in place of the 5-pin DIN.
[src:web-midi/midi-p02] It was released in the pre-MIDI years and later retrofitted with a MIDI interface but kept its XLR connector.
[src:web-midi/midi-p02] As computer-based studio setups became common, MIDI devices that could connect directly to a computer became available.
[src:web-midi/midi-p02] These typically used the 8-pin mini-DIN connector that was used by Apple for serial ports prior to the introduction of the Blue and White G3 models.
[src:web-midi/midi-p02] MIDI interfaces intended for use as the centerpiece of a studio, such as the Mark of the Unicorn MIDI Time Piece, were made possible by a fast transmission mode that could take advantage of these serial ports' ability to operate at 20 times the standard MIDI speed.
[src:web-midi/midi-p02] Mini-DIN ports were built into some late-1990s MIDI instruments so they could connect directly to a computer.
[src:web-midi/midi-p02] Some devices connected via a PCs' DB-25 parallel port, or through the DA-15 game port found on many PC sound cards.
[src:web-midi/midi-p02] Yamaha introduced the mLAN protocol in 1999.
[src:web-midi/midi-p02] No new mLan products have been released since 2007.
[src:web-midi/midi-p02] SCSI Musical Data Interchange (SMDI) is a method of using SCSI to transfer information between samplers and computers.
[src:web-midi/midi-p02] SMDI uses SCSI instead of SDS to transfer sample data between devices.
[src:web-midi/midi-p02] SDMI was used by some samplers and hard disk recorders in the 1990s (e.g.
[src:web-midi/midi-p02] Kurzweil K2000 and Peavey SP Sample Playback Synthesizer) for fast bidirectional sample transport to hard disk drives and magneto-optical drives.
[src:web-midi/midi-p02] Computer network implementations of MIDI provide network routing capabilities, and the high-bandwidth channel that earlier alternatives to MIDI, such as ZIPI, were intended to bring.
[src:web-midi/midi-p02] Proprietary implementations have existed since the 1980s, some of which use fiber optic cables for transmission.
[src:web-midi/midi-p02] The Internet Engineering Task Force's RTP-MIDI open specification has gained industry support.
[src:web-midi/midi-p02] Apple has supported this protocol from Mac OS X 10.4 onwards, and a Windows driver based on Apple's implementation exists for Windows XP and newer versions.
[src:web-midi/midi-p02] Systems for wireless MIDI transmission have been available since the 1980s.
[src:web-midi/midi-p02] Several commercially available transmitters allow wireless transmission of MIDI and OSC signals over Wi-Fi and Bluetooth. iOS devices are able to function as MIDI control surfaces, using Wi-Fi and OSC.
[src:web-midi/midi-p02] An XBee radio can be used to build a wireless MIDI transceiver as a do-it-yourself project.
[src:web-midi/midi-p02] Android devices are able to function as full MIDI control surfaces using several different protocols over Wi-Fi and Bluetooth.
[src:web-midi/midi-p02] The MIDI 2.0 standard was unveiled on January 17, 2020, at the Winter NAMM Show in Anaheim, California.
[src:web-midi/midi-p02] Representatives Yamaha, ROLI, Microsoft, Google, and the MIDI Association introduced the update, which enables bidirectional communication while maintaining backward compatibility.
[src:web-midi/midi-p02] Research on the new MIDI protocol began in 2005.
[src:web-midi/midi-p02] Prototype devices showcasing wired and wireless connections have been shown privately at NAMM.
[src:web-midi/midi-p02] Licensing and product certification policies have been developed, although no projected release date was announced.
[src:web-midi/midi-p02] Proposed physical layer and transport layer included Ethernet-based protocols such as RTP MIDI and Audio Video Bridging/Time-Sensitive Networking, as well as User Datagram Protocol (UDP)-based transport.
[src:web-midi/midi-p02] AMEI and MMA announced that complete specifications will be published following interoperability testing of prototype implementations from major manufacturers such as Google, Yamaha, Steinberg, Roland, Ableton, Native Instruments, and ROLI, among others.
[src:web-midi/midi-p02] In January 2020, Roland announced the A-88mkII controller keyboard that supports MIDI 2.0.
[src:web-midi/midi-p02] MIDI 2.0 includes MIDI Capability Inquiry specification for property exchange and profiles, and the new Universal MIDI Packet format for high-speed transports which supports both MIDI 1.0 and MIDI 2.0 voice messages.
[src:web-midi/midi-p02] Some devices operating MIDI 1.0 can "retrofit" some 2.0 features.
[src:web-midi/midi-p02] Since its release in early January 2020 by the MIDI Manufacturers Association, more details have yet to come out about the new update.
[src:web-midi/midi-p02] As of 2021 there were five components to MIDI such as; M2-100-U v1.0 MIDI 2.0 Specification Overview, M2-101-UM v1.1 MIDI-CI Specification, M2-102-U v1.0 Common Rules for MIDI-CI Profiles, M2-103-UM v1.0 Common Rules for MIDI-CI PE and M2-104-UM v1.0 UMP and MIDI 2.0 Protocol Specification.
[src:web-midi/midi-p02] Other specifications regarding MIDI 2.0 include: allowing the use of 32,000 controllers and wide range note enhancements.
[src:web-midi/midi-p02] These enhancements are made better through the property exchange.
[src:web-midi/musical-note] In music, **notes** are distinct and isolatable sounds that act as the most basic building blocks for nearly all of music.
[src:web-midi/musical-note] This discretization facilitates performance, comprehension, and analysis.
[src:web-midi/musical-note] Notes may be visually communicated by writing them in musical notation.
[src:web-midi/musical-note] Notes can distinguish the general pitch class or the specific pitch played by a pitched instrument.
[src:web-midi/musical-note] Although this article focuses on pitch, notes for unpitched percussion instruments distinguish between different percussion instruments (and/or different manners to sound them) instead of pitch.
[src:web-midi/musical-note] Note value expresses the relative duration of the note in time.
[src:web-midi/musical-note] Dynamics for a note indicate how loud to play them.
[src:web-midi/musical-note] Articulations may further indicate how performers should shape the attack and decay of the note and express fluctuations in a note's timbre and pitch.
[src:web-midi/musical-note] Notes may even distinguish the use of different extended techniques by using special symbols.
[src:web-midi/musical-note] The term *note* can refer to a specific musical event, for instance when saying the song "Happy Birthday to You", begins with two notes of identical pitch.
[src:web-midi/musical-note] A note can have a note value that indicates the note's duration relative to the musical meter.
[src:web-midi/musical-note] Longer note values (e.g. the longa) and shorter note values (e.g. the two hundred fifty-sixth note) do exist, but are very rare in modern times.
[src:web-midi/musical-note] These durations can further be subdivided using tuplets.
[src:web-midi/musical-note] Furthermore, a tie can combine two notes together to create a more specific duration which cannot be represented by a single note's value.
[src:web-midi/musical-note] A rhythm is formed from a sequence in time of consecutive notes and rests (the space between notes) of various durations.
[src:web-midi/musical-note] Rhythms are agnostic to pitches, so if a melody is transposed to a different scale, its rhythm will remain constant.
[src:web-midi/musical-note] Music theory in most European countries and others use the solfège naming convention.
[src:web-midi/musical-note] Fixed do uses the syllables *re–mi–fa–sol–la–si* specifically for the C major scale, while movable do labels notes of *any* major scale with that same order of syllables.
[src:web-midi/musical-note] Alternatively, particularly in English- and some Dutch-speaking regions, and certainly in all of Germany, pitch classes are typically represented by the first seven letters of the Latin alphabet (A, B, C, D, E, F and G), corresponding to the A minor scale.
[src:web-midi/musical-note] Several European countries, including Germany and Czechia, use H instead of B (see § 12-tone chromatic scale for details).
[src:web-midi/musical-note] Byzantium used the names *Pa–Vu–Ga–Di–Ke–Zo–Ni* (Πα–Βου–Γα–Δι–Κε–Ζω–Νη).
[src:web-midi/musical-note] A single note is sometimes called a monad.
[src:web-midi/musical-note] In traditional Indian music, musical notes are called svaras and commonly represented using the seven notes, Sa, Re, Ga, Ma, Pa, Dha and Ni.
[src:web-midi/musical-note] In a score, each note is assigned a specific vertical position on a staff position (a line or space) on the staff, as determined by the clef.
[src:web-midi/musical-note] Each line or space is assigned a note name.
[src:web-midi/musical-note] These names are memorized by musicians and allow them to know at a glance the proper pitch to play on their instruments.
[src:web-midi/musical-note] The staff above shows the notes C, D, E, F, G, A, B, C and then in reverse order, with no key signature or accidentals.
[src:web-midi/musical-note] Notes that belong to the diatonic scale relevant in a tonal context are called *diatonic notes*.
[src:web-midi/musical-note] Notes that do not meet that criterion are called *chromatic notes* or *accidentals*.
[src:web-midi/musical-note] Accidental symbols visually communicate a modification of a note's pitch from its tonal context.
[src:web-midi/musical-note] Most commonly, the sharp symbol (♯) raises a note by a half step, while the flat symbol (♭) lowers a note by a half step.
[src:web-midi/musical-note] This half step interval is also known as a semitone (which has an equal temperament frequency ratio of 12√2 ≅ 1.0595).
[src:web-midi/musical-note] The natural symbol (♮) indicates that any previously applied accidentals should be cancelled.
[src:web-midi/musical-note] Advanced musicians use the double-sharp symbol ((double sharp)) to raise the pitch by two semitones, the double-flat symbol ((double flat)) to lower it by two semitones, and even more advanced accidental symbols (e.g. for quarter tones).
[src:web-midi/musical-note] Accidental symbols are placed to *the right* of a note's letter when written in text (e.g.
[src:web-midi/musical-note] F♯ is F-sharp, B♭ is B-flat, and C♮ is C natural), but are placed to *the left* of a note's head when drawn on a staff.
[src:web-midi/musical-note] Systematic alterations to any of the 7 lettered pitch classes are communicated using a key signature.
[src:web-midi/musical-note] When drawn on a staff, accidental symbols are positioned in a key signature to indicate that those alterations apply to all occurrences of the lettered pitch class corresponding to each symbol's position.
[src:web-midi/musical-note] Additional explicitly-noted accidentals can be drawn next to noteheads to override the key signature for all subsequent notes with the same lettered pitch class in that bar.
[src:web-midi/musical-note] However, this effect does not accumulate for subsequent accidental symbols for the same pitch class.
[src:web-midi/musical-note] Assuming enharmonicity, accidentals can create pitch equivalences between different notes (e.g. the note B♯ represents the same pitch as the note C).
[src:web-midi/musical-note] Thus, a 12-note chromatic scale adds 5 pitch classes in addition to the 7 lettered pitch classes.
[src:web-midi/musical-note] The following chart lists names used in different countries for the 12 pitch classes of a chromatic scale built on C.
[src:web-midi/musical-note] Their corresponding symbols are in parentheses.
[src:web-midi/musical-note] Differences between German and English notation are highlighted in **bold** typeface.
[src:web-midi/musical-note] Although the English and Dutch names are different, the corresponding symbols are identical.
[src:web-midi/musical-note] Two pitches that are any number of octaves apart (i.e. their fundamental frequencies are in a ratio equal to a power of two) are perceived as very similar.
[src:web-midi/musical-note] Because of that, all notes with these kinds of relations can be grouped under the same pitch class and are often given the same name.
[src:web-midi/musical-note] The top note of a musical scale is the bottom note's second harmonic and has double the bottom note's frequency.
[src:web-midi/musical-note] Because both notes belong to the same pitch class, they are often called by the same name.
[src:web-midi/musical-note] That top note may also be referred to as the "octave" of the bottom note, since an octave is the interval between a note and another with double frequency.
[src:web-midi/musical-note] Middle **C** is often used as a common reference point when discussing octaves.
[src:web-midi/musical-note] This is the **C** between the typical treble and bass staves; either one ledger line below the treble staff, or one ledger line above the bass.
[src:web-midi/musical-note] In standard tuning it has a pitch of 261.626 Hz.
[src:web-midi/musical-note] Middle **C** is a convenient reference, as it can be played on most common instruments.
[src:web-midi/musical-note] It can be sung by both male and female singers.
[src:web-midi/musical-note] It also falls near the middle of a standard 88-key piano.
[src:web-midi/musical-note] The most common tuning, the A440 pitch standard, defines the **A** above middle **C** to be exactly 440 Hz.
[src:web-midi/musical-note] Several nomenclature systems for differentiating pitches that have the same pitch class but which fall into different octaves.
[src:web-midi/musical-note] Helmholtz pitch notation, which distinguishes octaves using prime symbols and letter case of the pitch class letter.
[src:web-midi/musical-note] The MIDI standard for electronic musical instruments doesn't specifically designate pitch classes, but instead names pitches sequentially.
[src:web-midi/musical-note] For instance, the standard 440 Hz tuning pitch is named **A**4 in scientific notation, **a′** in Helmholtz notation, and number 69 in MIDI.
[src:web-midi/musical-note] Pitch is associated with the frequency of physical oscillations measured in hertz (Hz) representing the number of these oscillations per second.
[src:web-midi/musical-note] While notes can have any arbitrary frequency, notes in more consonant music tend to have pitches with simpler mathematical ratios to each other.
[src:web-midi/musical-note] Western music defines pitches around a central reference "concert pitch" of A4, currently standardized as 440 Hz.
[src:web-midi/musical-note] Octaves automatically yield powers of two times the original frequency, since h can be expressed as $12v$ when h is a multiple of 12 (with v being the number of octaves up or down).
[src:web-midi/musical-note] Cents are a convenient unit for humans to express finer divisions of this logarithmic scale that are 1⁄100th of an equally-tempered semitone.
[src:web-midi/musical-note] Since one semitone equals 100 cents, one octave equals 12 ⋅ 100 cents = 1200 cents.
[src:web-midi/musical-note] Cents correspond to a *difference* in this logarithmic scale, however in the regular linear scale of frequency, adding 1 cent corresponds to *multiplying* a frequency by 1200√2 (≅ 1.000578).
[src:web-midi/musical-note] 69 is the number of semitones between C−1 (MIDI note 0) and A4.
[src:web-midi/musical-note] Music notation systems have used letters of the alphabet for centuries.
[src:web-midi/musical-note] Though it is not known whether this was his devising or common usage at the time, this is nonetheless called *Boethian notation*.
[src:web-midi/musical-note] A modified form of Boethius' notation later appeared in the *Dialogus de musica* (ca.
[src:web-midi/musical-note] 1000) by Pseudo-Odo, in a discussion of the division of the monochord.
[src:web-midi/musical-note] Following this, the range (or compass) of used notes was extended to three octaves, and the system of repeating letters **A**–**G** in each octave was introduced, these being written as lower-case for the second octave (**a**–**g**) and double lower-case letters for the third (**aa**–**gg**).
[src:web-midi/musical-note] When the range was extended down by one note, to a **G**, that note was denoted using the Greek letter gamma (**Γ**), the lowest note in Medieval music notation.
[src:web-midi/musical-note] The remaining five notes of the chromatic scale (the black keys on a piano keyboard) were added gradually; the first being **B**♭, since **B** was flattened in certain modes to avoid the dissonant tritone interval.
[src:web-midi/musical-note] This change was not always shown in notation, but when written, **B**♭ (**B** flat) was written as a Latin, cursive "𝒷", and **B**♮ (**B** natural) a Gothic script (known as Blackletter) or "hard-edged" 𝔟.
[src:web-midi/musical-note] These evolved into the modern flat (♭) and natural (♮) symbols respectively.
[src:web-midi/musical-note] In parts of Europe, including Germany, Czechia, Slovakia, Poland, Hungary, Norway, Denmark, Serbia, Croatia, Slovenia, Finland, and Iceland (as well as Sweden before the 1990s), the Gothic 𝔟 transformed into the letter **h**.
[src:web-midi/musical-note] Therefore, in current German music terminology, **H** is used instead of **B**♮ (**B** natural), and **B** instead of **B**♭ (**B** flat).
[src:web-midi/musical-note] In Italian, Portuguese, Spanish, French, Romanian, Greek, Albanian, Russian, Mongolian, Flemish, Persian, Arabic, Hebrew, Ukrainian, Bulgarian, Turkish and Vietnamese the note names are *do–re–mi–fa–sol–la–si* rather than **C–D–E–F–G–A–B**.
[src:web-midi/musical-note] These names follow the original names reputedly given by Guido d'Arezzo, who had taken them from the first syllables of the first six musical phrases of a Gregorian chant melody *Ut queant laxis*, whose successive lines began on the appropriate scale degrees.
[src:web-midi/musical-note] These became the basis of the solfège system.
[src:web-midi/musical-note] For ease of singing, the name *ut* was largely replaced by *do* (most likely from the beginning of *Dominus*, "Lord"), though *ut* is still used in some places.
[src:web-midi/musical-note] It was the Italian musicologist and humanist Giovanni Battista Doni (1595–1647) who successfully promoted renaming the name of the note from *ut* to *do*.
[src:web-midi/musical-note] For the seventh degree, the name *si* (from *Sancte Iohannes*, St.
[src:web-midi/musical-note] John, to whom the hymn is dedicated), though in some regions the seventh is named *ti* (again, easier to pronounce while singing).
[src:web-midi/requestmidiaccess] The **`requestMIDIAccess()`** method of the `Navigator` interface returns a `Promise` representing a request for access to MIDI devices on a user's system.
[src:web-midi/requestmidiaccess] This method is part of the Web MIDI API, which provides a means for accessing, enumerating, and manipulating MIDI devices.
[src:web-midi/requestmidiaccess] This method may prompt the user for access to MIDI devices available to their system, or it may use a previously established preference to grant or deny access.
[src:web-midi/requestmidiaccess] If permission is granted then the `Promise` resolves and a `MIDIAccess` object is returned.
[src:web-midi/requestmidiaccess] An `Object` representing options to pass into the method.
[src:web-midi/requestmidiaccess] A `Boolean` value that, if set to `true`, allows the ability to send and receive system exclusive (sysex) messages.
[src:web-midi/requestmidiaccess] A `Boolean` value that, if set to `true`, allows the system to utilize any installed software synthesizers.
[src:web-midi/requestmidiaccess] A `Promise` that resolves with a `MIDIAccess` object.
[src:web-midi/requestmidiaccess] Thrown if the document or page is closed due to user navigation.
[src:web-midi/requestmidiaccess] Thrown if the underlying system raises any errors.
[src:web-midi/requestmidiaccess] Thrown if the feature or options are not supported by the system.
[src:web-midi/requestmidiaccess] Thrown if the user or system denies the application from creating a MIDIAccess object with the requested options, or if the document is not allowed to use the feature (for example, because of a Permission Policy, or because the user previously denied a permission request).
[src:web-midi/requestmidiaccess] In the following example, the `Navigator.requestMIDIAccess()` method returns the `MIDIAccess` object, which gives access to information about the input and output MIDI ports.
[src:web-midi/web-midi-api] The Web MIDI API connects to and interacts with Musical Instrument Digital Interface (MIDI) Devices.
[src:web-midi/web-midi-api] The interfaces deal with the practical aspects of sending and receiving MIDI messages.
[src:web-midi/web-midi-api] Therefore, the API can be used for musical and non-musical uses, with any MIDI device connected to your computer.
[src:web-midi/web-midi-api] Represents all of the available MIDI input ports.
[src:web-midi/web-midi-api] Represents all of the available MIDI output ports.
[src:web-midi/web-midi-api] Provides the methods to list input and output devices, and to access an individual device.
[src:web-midi/web-midi-api] Provides a method for dealing with MIDI messages from an input port.
[src:web-midi/web-midi-api] Queues messages to the linked MIDI port.
[src:web-midi/web-midi-api] Messages can be sent immediately or after a specified delay.
[src:web-midi/web-midi-api] The event passed to the `MIDIInput` `midimessage` event.
[src:web-midi/web-midi-api] The event passed to the `MIDIAccess` `statechange` and `MIDIPort` `statechange` events, when a port becomes available or unavailable.
[src:web-midi/web-midi-api] Access to the API is requested using the `navigator.requestMIDIAccess()` method.
[src:web-midi/web-midi-api] The `navigator.requestMIDIAccess()` method returns a promise that resolves to a `MIDIAccess` object, which can then be used to access a MIDI device.
[src:web-midi/web-midi-api] The method must be called in a secure context.
[src:web-midi/web-midi-api] In this example the list of input and output ports are retrieved and printed to the console.
[src:web-midi/web-midi-api] This example prints all MIDI input messages to the console.
